pgTitle: List of Vanity Fair (British magazine) caricatures (1905–09)

rows.text: The last of the classical school
His religion is the worship of all sorts of winged and finny freaks
He has engineered nothing better than his own fortunes
He was born a Serene Highness but has lived it down
Extinction, Distinction – which will it be? Something of both at present, say the spiteful
A gentle shepherd who would lead his flock in to the protectionist fold
He insists that his pen is mightier than his sword
The Labourer is worthy of his hire
Chairman of Committees in the Lords
He has decided where Churches disagree
Oh, child may'st thou be less talkative than thy father, But in all else like him
To abandon Conservative ideals is to destroy the Empire
Magnetic, he has the power to infect almost everyone with the delight that he takes in himself
Though it is an arguable point whether he be, as it was once reputed, the most intellectual, he remains, beyond dispute, the dressiest of contemporary British dramatists
So voluble an Advocate should become a successful Parliamentarian
A man Right Reverend and Well-Beloved
He patronises literature and the turf, but does not waste his money
He does not under-estimate his own ability
A Celebrated Oarsman who prefers cricket to rowing and golf to both
A man of Law and Broad Acres
The Rt Hon Sir Nicholas Roderick O'Conor
The Hon Mr Justice CJ Darling
Grand Duke Michael Michaelovitch of Russia
The Rt Hon Frederick Leverton Harris MP
